  <body>
    <segment id="1" parent="24" relname="background">Perhaps some shovelers should look at the latest superhyped recycling of the
&quot;blacks are mentally inferior&quot; argument (Time, Newseek, NYT, some tv shows
all reported on this story, the authors&apos; names escape me).</segment>
    <segment id="2" parent="24" relname="span">

Would self-proclaimed relativists avoid addressing the shoddiness of the
argument?</segment>
    <segment id="3" parent="2" relname="elaboration"> On the other hand, would a too-narrow focus on the details of
statistical inference and the like miss some crucial opportunities as well?</segment>
    <segment id="4" parent="25" relname="span">
It seems to me the value of constructivism is it allows multiple sites of
intervention in the debate,</segment>
    <segment id="5" parent="4" relname="elaboration"> e.g. historical context--racist theories in
science are nothing new nor can they _always_ just be fitted in the &quot;poor
methodology&quot; category.</segment>
    <segment id="6" parent="4" relname="elaboration"> What is the relationship between one of the authors&apos;
position at the American Enterprise Institute, their attacks on welfare
and the shaping of research questions and strategies?</segment>
    <segment id="7" parent="19" relname="span"> How effective are the
usual types of critiques (e.g. Lewontin and company) at actually affecting
directions of research and the like</segment>
    <segment id="8" parent="18" relname="span"> and how does this relate to the division
of labor in science and the problem-solving interest in certain types of
questions </segment>
    <segment id="16" parent="8" relname="elaboration">(e.g. internal development of IQ testing since it presents new
puzzles, despite critique of the assumptions from a variety of perspectives,
analagous to Pickering&apos;s _Constructing Quarks_ perhaps).</segment>
    <segment id="9" parent="4" relname="elaboration">
How does this relate to the differential positions of women and minorities
in science?</segment>
    <segment id="10" parent="4" relname="elaboration"> to prevailing political moods?</segment>
    <segment id="11" parent="20" relname="sequence"> Why is the press so enthusiastic
in presenting this</segment>
    <segment id="12" parent="20" relname="sequence"> and what has been the response by scientist-critics and
professional organizations? </segment>
    <segment id="13" parent="4" relname="elaboration">How does IQ testing and related technologies
_already_ parcel people out on the basis of race and class?</segment>
    <segment id="14" parent="15" relname="concession">

Constructivism clearly has much to offer here</segment>
    <segment id="15" parent="21" relname="span"> but only if it can shovel the
shit while simultaneously working on a more long-term sanitation system.</segment>
